itabh-bachchan-ranveer-singh-bag-gq-awards/167826.html|publisher= thestatesman.com |accessdate=2016-09-29|date=29 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= GQ Awards 2016 winners list: Ranveer Singh, Kangana Ranaut, Amitabh Bachchan win top honours|url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/gq-awards-2016-winners-list-ranveer-singh-kangana-ranaut-amitabh-bachchan-win-top-honours-1519517/|publisher= india.com|accessdate=2016-09-29|date=29 September 2016}}</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 Femina Beauty Awards: Style Legend Of All Time.<ref>{{cite web|title= Femina Beauty Awards 2018: Amitabh Bachchan, Aishwarya Rai bag awards|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/femina-beauty-awards-2018-winners-photos-amitabh-bachchan-aishwarya-rai-rekha-5066378/|publisher= indianexpress.com|accessdate=2018-02-16|date=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n* 2018 - [[Sayaji Ratna Award]] by [[Baroda Management Association]] <ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/amitabh-bachchan-to-be-given-sayaji-ratna-award/articleshow/66467721.cms Amitabh Bachchan to be given Sayaji Ratna Award, The Times of India, 3-Nov-2018]</ref>\n\n==Madame Tussauds==\n* In June 2000, Bachchan became the first living Asian to have been immortalised in wax at Madame Tussauds London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/news/art-of-cinema-is-a-small-contribution-amitabh-bachchan/441709/ |title=Art of cinema is a small contribution: Amitabh Bachchan |publisher=Screenindia.com |date=2009-04-01 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604212708/http://www.screenindia.com/news/art-of-cinema-is-a-small-contribution-amitabh-bachchan/441709 |archivedate= 4 June 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madametussauds.com/London/OurFigures/Bollywoodstars/AmitabhBachchan/Default.aspx |title=Amitabh Bachchan's wax figure at Madame Tussauds London |publisher=Madametussauds.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* In May 2009, a lifelike wax figure of Bachchan has been unveiled at the newly launched 'Bollywood Zone' in Madame Tussauds at Times Square in New York.<ref>{{cite web|author=Agencies |url=http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/big-bs-wax-statue-unveiled-at-madame-tussauds-new-york.html |title=Big B's wax statue unveiled at Madame Tussauds New York \u2013 Bollywood News |publisher=ApunKaChoice.Com |date=2009-05-23 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224031209/http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/big-bs-wax-statue-unveiled-at-madame-tussauds-new-york.html |archivedate=24 February 2012 }}</ref>\n* In March 2011, Bachchan's wax image has been unveiled at the \"World Famous Home of the Famous\" Madame Tussauds Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article1570825.ece |title= Amitabh's wax statue unveiled at Hong Kong Tussauds |publisher=thehindu.com |date=2011-03-25 |accessdate=2012-10-11 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://gulfnews.com/arts-entertainment/celebrity/amitabh-bachchan-is-the-first-bollywood-actor-to-get-a-wax-figure-1.783136 |title= Amitabh Bachchan is the first Bollywood actor to get a wax figure |publisher= gulfnews.com |date=2011-03-27 |accessdate=2012-10-11}}</ref>\n* In August 2011, Bachchan's wax image has been unveiled at Madame Tussauds museum Bangkok.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madametussauds.com/Bangkok/en/NewsAndEvents/AmitabhBachchanLaunch.aspx |title=Unveils wax figure of India's all-time superstar: Amitabh Bachchan |publisher=madametussauds.com/Bangkok |date=2011-08-24 |accessdate=2012-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114095003/http://www.madametussauds.com/Bangkok/en/NewsAndEvents/AmitabhBachchanLaunch.aspx |archivedate=14 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypakistan.com/NewsDetails/12199/Amitabh-Bachan%E2%80%99s-wax-figure-unveiled-in-Bangkok.aspx |title=Amitabh Bachan's wax figure unveiled in Bangkok |publisher=dailypakistan.com |date=2011-08-24 |accessdate=2012-10-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022031618/http://www.dailypakistan.com/NewsDetails/12199/Amitabh-Bachan%E2%80%99s-wax-figure-unveiled-in-Bangkok.aspx |archivedate=22 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thailandtourismupdate.com/TravelIndustryReleaseInfo/77/162/MADAME-TUSSAUDS-BANGKOK-UNVEILS-WAX-FIGURE-OF-INDIA\u2019S-SUPERSTAR |title= MADAME TUSSAUDS BANGKOK UNVEILS WAX FIGURE OF INDIA'S SUPERSTAR |publisher= thailandtourismupdate.com |date= 2011-09-08 |accessdate= 2012-10-12 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120630152637/http://www.thailandtourismupdate.com/TravelIndustryReleaseInfo/77/162/MADAME-TUSSAUDS-BANGKOK-UNVEILS-WAX-FIGURE-OF-INDIA%E2%80%99S-SUPERSTAR |archivedate= 30 June 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n* On 5 December 2012, Bachchan's wax image has been unveiled at Madame Tussauds museum Washington, DC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?section=Movies&Id=300783&keyword=bollywood&subcatg=MOVIESINDIA&nid=300783 |title=Amitabh Bachchan, Shah Rukh Khan, Aishwarya Rai join Washington Tussauds |publisher=ndtv.com |date=2012-12-05 |accessdate=2012-12-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130111063100/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?section=Movies&Id=300783&keyword=bollywood&subcatg=MOVIESINDIA&nid=300783 |archivedate=11 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/big-b-srk-aishwaryas-wax-figures-at-washington-tussauds/1040813/ |title= Big B, SRK, Aishwarya's wax figures at Washington Tussauds |publisher= indianexpress.com |date=2012-12-05 |accessdate=2012-12-05}}</ref>\n* On 13 January 2017, Bachchan's wax image has been unveiled at Madame Tussauds museum Delhi.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==International honours and recognition==\n* In July 1999, Bachchan was named the \"Greatest Star of stage or screen of the Millennium\" by BBC online poll where he defeated many [[Hollywood]] legends such as [[Alec Guinness]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Laurence Olivier]] and [[Charlie Chaplin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/381017.stm | work=BBC News | title=Bollywood star tops the poll | date=1 July 1999}}</ref>\n* In 2001, he was ranked as the \"Most Powerful Indian Film Star\" by [[Forbes]].<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.forbes.com/2001/03/09/0309bollywood_print.html |title= India's Celebrity Film Stars |publisher= forbes.com |date=2001-03-09 |accessdate=2012-10-14 |first=Todd |last=Jatras}}</ref>\n* On 10 September 2001 he was awarded the \"Actor of the Century\" award at the [[Alexandria International Film Festival]]. [[Egypt]]ian Minister of Culture [[Farouk Hosni]] presented Bachchan with the award in recognition of his contribution to international cinema.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20010904/world.htm#8 |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India \u2013 World |publisher=Tribuneindia.com |date=2001-09-04 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* On 14 March 2003, he was conferred with the honorary citizenship of the French town of [[Deauville]] at the fifth edition of the [[Deauville Asian Film Festival|Asian film festival]]. An honour earlier bestowed on only two people, Queen [[Elizabeth II]] and the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] space hero, [[Yuri Gagarin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2003/07/04/stories/2003070400980100.htm | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title='Shahenshah' of Bollywood | date=4 July 2003}}</ref>\n* In October 2003, he was conferred with the Medal of Honour of Morocco, given to him by King Mohammed at the [[International Film Festival of Marrakech|Marrakech International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Marrakech\"/><ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\"/> \n* In October 2003, [[TIME]] magazine dubbed Bachchan as \"the Undisputed Godfather of Bollywood\".<ref name=\"Perry\"/> He was also featured in its list of Bollywood's Brightest Stars.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/photoessays/bollywood/players5.html |work=Time |date=27 October 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011132013/http://www.time.com/time/asia/photoessays/bollywood/players5.html |archivedate=11 October 2008 }}</ref>\n* In April 2005, The [[Walter Reade Theater]] of [[Lincoln Center]] in [[New York City|New York]] honored Amitabh Bachchan with a special tribute, retrospective\u2014titled \"Amitabh Bachchan: The Biggest Film Star in the World\".<ref name=\"Saltz\"/><ref name=\"thedailybeast.com/newsweek\"/> The tribute also included \"An Evening with Amitabh Bachchan\", a live appearance by Bachchan hosted at the Lincoln Center's Alice Tully Hall.<ref name=\"An Evening with Amitabh Bachchan\">{{cite web| title=iaac.us| work=Join Amitabh Bachchan for the evening| url=http://www.iaac.us/ab_amitabh.htm| accessdate=11 March 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070415233159/http://www.iaac.us/ab_amitabh.htm| archive-date=15 April 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* He was honoured along with actors and directors from Hollywood at an International Film Festival in Rabat, Morocco.<ref name=\"Joining the ranks\">{{cite news | title=hindu.com| work=Joining the ranks of Hollywood|url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/09/07/stories/2003090701192000.htm| accessdate=11 March 2007| location=Chennai, India| date=7 September 2003}}</ref>\n* In the weekend of 16 and 17 June June 2007, the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] (BAFTA) hosts a Bachchan spectacular retrospective to honour Bachchan's stellar career. The Chairman of BAFTA ended the event by announcing Bachchan as an honorary Life-Time member of BAFTA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2007/06/27/2800/index.html |title=Amitabh Bachchan on being honoured by BAFTA |publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com |date=2007-06-27 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129061410/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2007/06/27/2800/index.html |archivedate=29 November 2011 }}</ref>\n* On 22 November 2007 he was honoured by the London Mayor Ken Livingstone with \"The Visit London Special Award for Outstanding Achievement\" for his contribution to Indian cinema in the last 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeenews.com/znnew/articles.asp?aid=408976&ssid=1&ssname=Movies%20and%20Theatre&sid=ENT&sname= |accessdate=23 November 2007 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n* On 15 January 2009,  Le Salon du Cinema (Cinema Fair) in Paris paid tribute to Indian Cinema for their new edition, with Bachchan being the guest of honour. He also launched a retrospective of his films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2009/01/15/12433/index.html |title=Bachchans to attend Le Salon du Cinema in Paris as Big B's films will be screened |publisher=Bollywoodhungama.com |date=2009-01-15 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* On 31 January 2009, he was honoured with the World Economic Forum's Crystal Award at Davos for his contribution to the world of art.<ref>{{cite web|author=Monday, 2 February 2009 at 2337 hrs IST |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/wef-honours-amitabh-with-crystal-award/417839/ |title=WEF honours Amitabh with Crystal Award |publisher=Financialexpress.com |date=2009-02-02 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* In 2009, the Tehran Film Festival has invited Bachchan to receive the Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/index_View.asp?code=185682 |title=Fajr filmfest to honor Amitabh Bachchan |publisher=tehran times |date=2008-12-27 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* In December 2009, he was honoured with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the Dubai International Film Festival for his outstanding contribution to cinema.<ref>{{cite web|author=Your name |url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/amitabh-bachchan-wins-lifetime-achievement-award-65881.html |title=Amitabh Bachchan wins lifetime achievement award |publisher=ArabianBusiness.com |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003013953/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/amitabh-bachchan-wins-lifetime-achievement-award-65881.html |archivedate=3 October 2012 }}</ref>\n* In December 2009, he was honoured with the 8th Asian Film Cultural Award for his contribution to cinema for 40 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Big-B-conferred-Asian-Film-Cultural-Award/H1-Article1-484231.aspx |title=Big B conferred Asian Film Cultural Award |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125734/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Big-B-conferred-Asian-Film-Cultural-Award/H1-Article1-484231.aspx |archivedate=6 June 2011 }}</ref>\n* In February 2010, he was honoured with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the Sixth Muscat, Oman International Film Festival (Miff).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofoman.com/echoice.asp?detail=33735 |title=TimesofOman.com |publisher=TimesofOman.com |date=2010-02-19 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725231841/http://www.timesofoman.com/echoice.asp?detail=33735 |archivedate=25 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omantribune.com/index.php?page=news&id=66134&heading=News%20in%20Details |title=the edge of knowledge |publisher=Oman Tribune |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715002102/http://www.omantribune.com/index.php?page=news&id=66134&heading=News%20in%20Details |archive-date=15 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In March 2010, he has been named the list of CNN's \"top 25 Asian actors of all time\".<ref name=\"Hindustan Times\"/>\n* In March 2010, he has won the Lifetime Achievement Award at the 34th [[Hong Kong International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Amitabh Bachchan Has Won the Lifetime Achievement Award at the 34th HKIFF=http://www.chinesefilms.cn/1/2010/03/18/41s389.htm|publisher= chinesefilms.cn |date=18 March 2010}}</ref>\n* In October 2010, he was honoured with a Lifetime Achievement Award at [[The Asian Awards]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bollyspice.com/1996/amitabh-bachchan-on-his-lifetime-achievement-award-at-uk-the-asian-awards |title=Amitabh Bachchan on his Lifetime Achievement Award at UK The Asian Awards}}</ref>\n* In April 2012, he was conferred the Polio Eradication Champion award by Rotary International for his invaluable support to the Polio Eradication Programme in India.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.unicef.org/india/media_7645.htm |title= Amitabh Bachchan conferred Polio Eradication Champion award |publisher= unicef.org |date=2012-04-19 |accessdate=2012-10-11}}</ref>\n* In July 2012, he was given the due honor to carry the Olympic torch during the last leg of its relay in London's Southwark.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-carries-olympic-torch-355100 |title= Amitabh Bachchan Carries Olympic Torch| date= 26 July 2012 | work=The Hollywood Reporter| first=Nyay| last=Bhushan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://olympicsmedaltally.com/amitabh-bachchan-carries-olympic-torch-in-london.html |title=Amitabh Bachchan carries Olympic torch in London |date=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203030918/http://olympicsmedaltally.com/amitabh-bachchan-carries-olympic-torch-in-london.html |archivedate=3 December 2012 }}</ref>\n* In November 2012, he was honoured by the Australian Government for his remarkable contribution to the Indian cinema, which is celebrating its centenary year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-11-22/news-interviews/35301713_1_amitabh-bachchan-indian-cinema-honour |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104005545/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-11-22/news-interviews/35301713_1_amitabh-bachchan-indian-cinema-honour |archive-date= 4 January 2013 |work=timesofindia |title=Amitabh Bachchan felicitated by Australian government |date=22 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.screenindia.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-honoured-by-australian-government/1035276/ | work= screenindia.com | title= Amitabh Bachchan honoured by Australian government | date= 23 November 2012 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://archive.today/20130203025550/http://www.screenindia.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-honoured-by-australian-government/1035276/ | archivedate= 3 February 2013 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n* In December 2012, he was honoured with the Tribute to Hindi Cinema Award at the 12th Marrakech International Film Festival.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://iplextra.indiatimes.com/photo/0eHU0zLcyJcOk?q=Morocco | work= timesofindia.com | title= MARRAKECH, MOROCCO | date= 1 December 2012 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.emirates247.com/news-in-images/shah-rukh-big-b-lead-bollywood-marrakech-parade-2012-12-03-1.485688 | work= emirates247.com | title= Shah Rukh, Big B lead Bollywood Marrakech parade | date=3 December 2012}}</ref>\n* On 10 December 2012, he was honoured with the \"Keys to the City of Florence\" at the [[River to River. Florence Indian Film Festival]] in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Big-B-receives-keys-to-city-of-Florence-feels-honoured/Article1-970935.aspx |title=Big B receives keys to city of Florence, feels honoured |publisher=hindustantimes.com |date=2012-12-10 |accessdate=2012-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211014856/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Big-B-receives-keys-to-city-of-Florence-feels-honoured/Article1-970935.aspx |archivedate=11 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-honoured-at-florence-film-festival/1042343 |title= Amitabh Bachchan honoured at Florence Film festival |publisher= indianexpress.com |date=2012-12-10 |accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/amitabh-bachchan-receives-keys-to-the-city-of-florence-view-pics/ |title= Amitabh Bachchan receives keys to the City of Florence: view pics |publisher= bollywoodlife.com |date=2012-12-10 |accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref>\n* In May 2013, he will be honoured with \"La Trobe University Global Citizenship Award\" by the [[La Trobe University]] in Melbourne. The University is also introducing a Phd Scholarship called Shri Amitabh Bachchan Scholarship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Amitabh-Bachchan-to-be-honoured-by-Australian-university/Article1-1049191.aspx |title=Amitabh Bachchan to be honoured by Australian university |date=23 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425180358/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Amitabh-Bachchan-to-be-honoured-by-Australian-university/Article1-1049191.aspx |archivedate=25 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southasiatimes.com.au/news/?p=3554 |title=La Trobe award for Amitabh Bachchan |date=23 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503072758/http://www.southasiatimes.com.au/news/?p=3554 |archivedate=3 May 2013 }}</ref>\n* In May 2013, he will be honoured with \"International Screen Icon\" award by the Victorian Government and the \"Ambassador of Goodwill\" award from the Vice Chancellor of La Trobe University in Melbourne.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/glamsham/article.aspx?cp-documentid=252741635 | title=Amitabh Bachchan to be honoured at Indian Film Festival of Melbourne | date=14 April 2013 | access-date=15 April 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416172822/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/glamsham/article.aspx?cp-documentid=252741635 | archive-date=16 April 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/scholarship-named-after-amitabh-bachchan-in-melbourne/1104367/ | title= Scholarship named after Amitabh Bachchan in Melbourne | date=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n* In September 2013, he was honoured with the \"Global Diversity Award\" in the British Parliament. Speaker of the House of Commons, presented the ornately sculpted glass Award to Bachchan and describing him as \"a Bollywood icon and the most famous Indian film star of all time\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/amitabh-bachchan-presented-with-global-diversity-award-2013/1/309399.html | title= Amitabh Amitabh Bachchan presented with Global Diversity Award 2013| date=12 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/amitabh-bachchan-to-get-global-diversity-award-417386| title= Amitabh Bachchan to get Global Diversity Award| date=11 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Amitabh-Bachchan-to-get-Global-Diversity-Award/articleshow/22483039.cms | title= Amitabh Bachchan to get Global Diversity Award| date=11 September 2013 | work=The Times Of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-to-be-honoured-with-global-diversity-award/1167649/ | title= Amitabh Bachchan to be honoured with Global Diversity Award | date=11 September 2013}}</ref>\n* In March 2014, he was honoured with the \"Global Icon of the Year\" award at the NRI of the Year awards.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-amitabh-bachchan-conferred-global-icon-of-the-year-award-1972140| title= Amitabh Amitabh Bachchan conferred Global Icon of the Year award| date=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n* In May 2014, he was honoured with the \"International Screen Icon\" award during the inaugural awards ceremony at the Indian Film Festival of Melbourne (IFFM).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofoman.com/News/33278/-Amitabh-Bachchan-honoured-with-International-Screen-Icon-award-at-Indian-Film-Festival-of-Melbourne |title=Amitabh Amitabh Bachchan honoured with International Screen Icon award at Indian Film Festival of Melbourne |date=3 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021131101/http://www.timesofoman.com/News/33278/-Amitabh-Bachchan-honoured-with-International-Screen-Icon-award-at-Indian-Film-Festival-of-Melbourne |archivedate=21 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Other recognition==\n* 2005 \u2013 Ranked as the \"Most popular Star in India\" by the Hansa Research's new syndicated study, Celebrity Track.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/09/11/stories/2005091102480300.htm |title=Bollywood stars score high on Celebrity Track |publisher=The Hindu Business Line |date=2005-09-11 |accessdate=2011-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927231836/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/09/11/stories/2005091102480300.htm |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2009 \u2013 He is called among the \"Top 5 Most Influential Indians of the Decade\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-01-28/people/28114794_1_sachin-tendulkar-master-blaster-cricketing | work=The Times Of India | title=Top 5 most influential Indians of the decade | date=2010-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Polls==\n* 2002 \u2013 Voted the \"Hottest Male Vegetarian\" by 'People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals' (PETA).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-09-17/news-interviews/27205136_1_vegetarian-diet-peta-india-yana-gupta | work=The Times Of India | title=Yana eclipses Pamela as hottest vegan | date=2003-09-17}}</ref>\n* 2003 \u2013 Voted the \"Greatest Actor\" in the film personalities category in the Best of India poll conducted by [[Zee News]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k3/aug/aug122.htm |title=Indiantelevision.com's Breaking News : Amitabh, Sachin top Zee News 'Best of India' poll |publisher=Indiantelevision.com |date=2003-08-16 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 Voted \"Entertainer of the Year\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-12-24/special-report/27830823_1_anil-ambani-voting-abhishek | work=The Times Of India | title=Achievers of the year | date=2006-12-24}}</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 Voted \"Real Star of Stars\" by reader's choice.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2006-12-31/news-interviews/27795939_1_megastar-rahul-dravid-dhoni | work=The Times Of India | title=Amitabh is the real star of stars | date=2006-12-31}}</ref>\n* 2008 \u2013 Voted \"Asia's Sexiest Vegetarian man\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petaasiapacific.com/feature-world_vegetarian_sexy.asp |title=Faye Wong and Amitabh Bachchan Voted Asia's Sexiest Vegetarian Celebrities, Abbie Cornish and Xavier Rudd Win in Australia &#124; Features |publisher=PETA Asia-Pacific |accessdate=2011-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209004348/http://www.petaasiapacific.com/feature-world_vegetarian_sexy.asp |archivedate=9 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* 2012 \u2013 Voted \"India's Greatest Actor\" in [[NDTV]] poll.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?ID=ENTEN20120213602&subcatg=MOVIESINDIA&keyword=bollywood&nid=260108 |title=NDTV poll: India's greatest actor is... |publisher=ndtv.com |date=2012-08-28 |accessdate=2012-08-28 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2012 \u2013 Voted \"Most-Admired Bollywood Actor\" in a new mobile survey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/amitabh-bachchan-sridevi-voted-mostadmired-bollywood-actors/1048607/ |title=Amitabh Bachchan, Sridevi voted most-admired Bollywood actors |publisher=indianexpress.com |date=2012-12-21 |accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n* 2012 \u2013 Voted the \"Hottest Male Vegetarian\" for the fourth time by 'People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals' (PETA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Amitabh-Bachchan-Vidya-Balan-named-hottest-vegetarians/Article1-984421.aspx |title=Amitabh Bachchan, Vidya Balan named hottest vegetarians |publisher=hindustantimes.com |date=2013-01-03 |accessdate=2013-01-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104141844/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Amitabh-Bachchan-Vidya-Balan-named-hottest-vegetarians/Article1-984421.aspx |archivedate=4 January 2013 }}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 Voted the \"Greatest Bollywood Star\" in a UK poll celebrating 100 years of Indian cinema.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-07-27/news-interviews/40832397_1_amitabh-bachchan-raj-kapoor-rajesh-khanna |title= Amitabh Bachchan crowned greatest Bollywood star |publisher= timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-07-27 |accessdate=2013-09-11}}</ref>\n* 2019 - Topped India Most Trusted Personality by TRA Research.\n* 2020- Topped India Most Trusted Personality by TRA Research.\n<ref><link rel=\"amphtml\" href=\"https://www.indiantelevision.com/mam/marketing/mam/big-b-is-india-s-most-trusted-personality-tra-research-190520?amp\" /></ref><ref><link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https://retropoplifestyle.com/old-is-gold-says-tras-most-desired-personality-list-2020/\" /></ref><ref><link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https://www.mediainfoline.com/tag/tras-most-desired-personality\" /></ref><ref><link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https://cornerpapes.com/2019/05/21/rajinikanth-is-south-indias-most-trusted-personality-2019-tra-research/\" /></ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of accolades received by Piku]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachchan, Amitabh}}\n[[Category:Lists of awards received by actor]]\n[[Category:Bollywood lists of awards and nominations]]\n[[Category:Amitabh Bachchan|Awards]]\n", "name_user": "124.123.226.239", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(No Tentioun)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Amitabh_Bachchan"}
{"title_page": "Barry Kerzin", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical person\n| name = Barry Kerzin\n| image = Barry Kerzin, American Professor of Medicine and Buddhist monk.gif\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Barry Michael Kerzin\n| birth_date = November 1, 1947\n| birth_place = Hollywood, USA\n| nationality = American\n| citizenship = [[United States of America]]\n| education = University of California at Berkeley (BA Philosophy) and University of Southern California (MD)\n| occupation = Teacher, physician, and Buddhist monk\n| known_for = Medical doctor to HH Dalai Lama and teacher at the interface of Buddhism and medicine\n| relations =\n| signature = \n| profession = \n| field =\n| work_institutions = Private practice (Ventura County, California)<br>[[University of Washington School of Medicine]] (Assistant Professor)<br>Private practice (charitable, [[Dharamshala]] India)<br>Human Values Institute (Japan)<br>Altruism in Medicine Institute (USA)<br>University of Hong Kong (Honorary)\n| specialism = \n| research_field = \n| prizes =\n| child = \n| module2 = \n|Publications=\"No Fear No Death: The Transformative Power of Compassion\", and \"N\u0101g\u0101rjuna\u2019s Wisdom: A Practitioner\u2019s Guide to the Middle Way\" (in press).\"Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness\", and \"Mind and Matter: Dialogue between Two Nobel Laureates\", in Japanese.}}\n\n'''Barry Michael Kerzin'''(born November 1, 1947) is an American physician and Buddhist monk.  He has lived in [[Dharamshala]] since 1988, and serves as a personal physician to the [[14th Dalai Lama]], along with treating people in the local community, free of charge. Following his ordination as a monk by HH Dalai Lama in January 2003, he has travelled widely, teaching and offering workshops in which he blends Buddhist teaching and his medical training, emphasizing the spiritual and health benefits of meditation and compassion.  He has served as a research participant in neuroscience research into [[Brain activity and meditation|the effects of meditation on the brain]].\n\nKerzin is an Affiliate Professor at the [[University of Washington Tacoma]], a Visiting Professor at the [[Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies|Central Institute of Tibetan Studies]], India, an Honorary Professor at the [[University of Hong Kong|University of Hong Kong (HKU)]], an Honorary Professor at the [[Mongolian National University of Medical Sciences]] (from October 2019), and a former Assistant Professor of Medicine at the [[University of Washington]]. He is a fellow at the [[Mind and Life Institute]] and consults for the [[Max Planck Institute for Medical Research|Max Planck Institute]] in Leipzig on compassion training.\n\nHe is founder and president of the Altruism in Medicine Institute (AIMI) and founder and chairman of the Human Values Institute (HVI) in Japan,\n\n==Early life and education ==\nKerzin was born in Hollywood, California on November 1, 1947.<ref name=Ventura/><ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: Month and day of birth and location at 3:29-3:35.</ref>  When he was young he read a book by [[D.T. Suzuki]]'s World of Zen, which sparked an interest in Buddhism.<ref name=caduc />   Starting at around six, he was plagued by questions of who he was and why he was here; they led him to join a philosophy club in high school and to switch to studying philosophy in college; he had started as a pre-med student.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 4:30-8:20.</ref>  He had wanted to become a doctor and did choose to continue on to medical school, because at the age of eleven he had a [[brain abscess]] that caused him to have seizures and fall into comas; it was eventually treated by a neurosurgeon with four brain surgeries over several years; the experience inspired him to become a doctor so that he could help other people.<ref name=caduc>{{cite web|author1=Yaya Huang |title=Mind the Gap \u2014An Interview with Prof. Barry Kerzin |url=http://www.hkucaduceus.net/Volume%2045/Issue2/int1.html |publisher=HKU Medical Faculty 'Caduceus' magazine 2014 |accessdate=31 March 2015 |location=Hong Kong |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402163838/http://www.hkucaduceus.net/Volume%2045/Issue2/int1.html |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKerzin received BA in Philosophy from the [[University of California at Berkeley]] and in 1976 he received an MD degree from the [[University of Southern California]].<ref name=USCCN /><ref name=AMIbio/>\n\n==Career==\nKerzin did his residency at [[Ventura County Medical Center]] and practiced family medicine in Ojai, California for seven years.<ref name=Ventura>{{cite news|last=Kim Lamb Gregory|title=Doctor/Tibetan monk returns to Ventura County to speak on mind, body|url=http://www.vcstar.com/news/a-physician-who-is-a-tibetan-monk-returns-to-to|newspaper=Ventura County Star|location=Ventura County, California|date=March 6, 2014|quote=Article says he is 66 years old. His birth year must be 1947 as he was born in November}}</ref>  His mother had died when he was 27, and just after he started working in Ojai, his wife was diagnosed with [[ovarian cancer]]. She died in 1983 and they had no children.<ref name=Ventura/>\n\nHe travelled in India, Sri Lanka, and Nepal for nearly a year, visiting several monasteries.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 8:40 - 9:35</ref>\n\nHe then obtained an appointment as an Assistant Professor of Medicine at the [[University of Washington School of Medicine]] from late 1985 to early 1989.<ref name=Ventura/><ref>[https://in.linkedin.com/pub/barry-kerzin/b6/937/832?trk=seokp_posts_secondary_cluster_res_author_name Barry Kerzin's LinkedIn Profile]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Page accessed August 9, 2015.  Source used for dates.</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, [[B. Alan Wallace]] and the [[Dharma Friendship Foundation]] coaxed a lama from Dharamsala, [[Gen Lamrimpa]], to come to Seattle for two years, and Kerzin served as his driver.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 9:30 - 10:15</ref>  In 1988 Gen Lamrimpa returned to India and Kerzin accompanied him, intending to take a six-month leave of absence from the University of Washington.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 15:25 - 17:00</ref>  He stayed in Dharamsala when his leave ended, and began providing free medical care to the local community, HH Dalai Lama and other Tibetan lamas.<ref name=Ventura/><ref name=USCCN>{{cite web|url=http://tfm.usc.edu/autumn-2013/class-notes-autumn-2013#1970s |publisher=USCTrojan Family |title=Barry Kerzin MD \u201976 (MED) |accessdate=March 30, 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402152211/http://tfm.usc.edu/autumn-2013/class-notes-autumn-2013 |archivedate=April 2, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=AMIbio/>  He also began studying Buddhism and meditation intensively, and 19 years after he moved there (in the early-2000s), he was ordained in Feb. 2003 as a Bikkshu (Buddhist monk) by HH Dalai Lama, and now cares for him as his doctor.<ref name=Ventura/><ref name=AMIbio/>  Throughout his career, Kerzin has maintained his board certification with the [[American Board of Family Medicine]].<ref name=AMIbio>Altruism in Medicine Institute [http://altruismmedicine.org/about/founder-dr-barry-kerzin/ About Dr. Barry Kerzin] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810131944/http://altruismmedicine.org/about/founder-dr-barry-kerzin/ |date=August 10, 2015 }} Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref>\n\nSince his ordination, Kerzin has been combining his work as a monk and doctor, harmonizing the mind and body, lecturing around the world in Japan, Hong Kong, Russia, Mongolia, Taiwan, Korea, Europe, and North America. He is teaching about the interface between [[medical science|modern medical science]] and [[Buddhism and psychology#Buddhism.27s phenomenological psychology|Buddhist psychology]] and [[Buddhist philosophy#Mahayana|philosophy]], with particular reference to [[altruism]] in medicine and [[secular ethics]] as well as [[Compassion#Buddhism|compassion]], [[Wisdom#Buddhism|wisdom]], [[Meditation#Buddhism|meditation]], death and dying and emotional hygiene (managing anger, jealousy, pride, etc.); he has also participated in neuroscience research on the effect of meditation on the brain.<ref name=caduc /><ref name=AMIbio/>\n\n[[File:Barry Kerzin meditating with EEG for neuroscience research.jpg|thumbnail|left|Kerzin meditating with EEG for neuroscience research]]\nIn the mid-2000s, he served as a research subject in neuroscience research into [[Brain activity and meditation|the effects of meditation on the brain]] led by Richard J Davidson at the [[University of Wisconsin]], as well as at [[Princeton University]].<ref>CNN. [http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0612/16/hcsg.01.html HOUSE CALL WITH DR. SANJAY GUPTA House Call with Dr. Sanjay Gupta. Encore Presentation: Happiness Cure] Aired December 16, 2006</ref> Kerzin has completed many meditation retreats, including a three-year retreat.\n\nKerzin founded the Human Values Institute in Japan in 2010 since teaching there regularly starting in 2007; he serves as chairman of the organization.<ref name=\"HVI\">Human Values Institute. [http://humanvaluesinstitute.org/purpose-methods/ HVI Purpose & Methods] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816015612/http://humanvaluesinstitute.org/purpose-methods/ |date=August 16, 2015 }} Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> The institute publishes books and instructional movies, gives lectures, leads workshops and meditation retreats, holds an annual symposium in Tokyo, and leads pilgrimages on the island of [[Shikoku#Traditions|Shikoku]]; the education focuses on healthy physical and emotional living and handling death compassionately.<ref name=\"HVI\" />  He taught about the [[Heart Sutra]] at the [[Gokoku-ji|Gokokuji Temple]] in Tokyo shortly after the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref>[http://issuu.com/dhardho/docs/thetibetpostinternational Tibet Post International March 32, 2011]. Tibetans and Japanese Hold Prayers for Victims of Tsunami. Page 1 and 6</ref> For HVI, Kerzin also works in juvenile prisons in Japan, and is developing well-being curricula, taught to doctors at [[St. Luke's International Hospital]] in Tokyo, and other hospitals and medical schools in Japan, e.g. Kyoto University, and leads meditation retreats at [[Mount Fuji|Mt. Fuji]].\n\nIn 2014, Kerzin founded the Altruism in Medicine Institute (AIMI) in the US.<ref>[https://opencorporates.com/companies/us_ca/C3624572 Altruism in Medicine Institute in the Open Corporates Database] Page accessed August 9, 2015]</ref> For AIMI, Kerzin gave a medical grand rounds lecture on compassion at Stanford Medical Schoo, and the Stanford CCARE], and in July lectured at Surgical Grand Rounds on the science behind meditation to the Ventura County Medical Center, as well as lectured at the [[University of Washington]]. In Spring 2016, he lectured at [[Oxford university|Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] Universities, and U.K. medical schools. Kerzin was the keynote speaker for the White Coast Ceremony for new first-year medical students at the [[University of Louisville School of Medicine]] in 2016 and again in 2018. In Fall 2016 he presented the plenary lecture to 800 Family Doctors at the Family Medicine Education Consortium in Pittsburgh, and in 2018 set the foundation for a Mindfulness-Compassion-Resilience training program for 18,000 nurses at UPMC. In Pittsburgh he was interviewed by many media outlets on his involvement with UPMC, the city of Pittsburgh, and his life mission of teaching mindfulness to doctors, nurses, and other professionals and leaders. One of the articles written on him is ''[https://postindustrial.com/featuredstories/the-dalai-lamas-doctor-has-a-message-for-pittsburgh/ The Dalai Lama's Doctor has a Message for Pittsburgh], ''and during his November 2019 visit, ''[https://pittsburghquarterly.com/pq-people-opinion/pq-opinion/item/2569-holiday-thoughts-from-the-dalai-lama-s-physician.html Holiday Thoughts From The Dalai Lama's Physician].'' In 2019, Kerzin led the 2-day program ''Developing Altruistic Algorithms Based on Buddhist Philosophy for Artificial Intelligence'', held at [[DeepMind]] (an Alphabet Group company) in London, UK. In 2020, he published the comment ''Beyond Empathy to Compassion'' in response to the powerful and moving article by George Gubernikoff, MD, entitled [https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2764713 ''Empathy Revisited'' (JAMA)]. \n\nHe participated in a 2011 weeklong workshop organized by scientists at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences]] in Leipzig, exploring the role that compassion training has in changing human behavior and emotions.<ref>[http://www.cbs.mpg.de/depts/singer/WorkshopConf Workshop \"How to Train Compassion\" 20.-23. July 2011, Studio Olafur, Berlin]</ref>  The workshop led to a documentary film and a multimedia book to which Kerzin contributed two chapters.<ref>[http://altruismmedicine.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Compassion_Web_2_Chapters.pdf Chapters 4 and 6] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402101215/http://altruismmedicine.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Compassion_Web_2_Chapters.pdf |date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHe had a visiting professorship at the Central University of Tibetan Studies, Varanasi, India in 2006.<ref name=HKUCV>HKU Centre of Buddhist Studies [http://www.buddhism.hku.hk/teaching_staff.htm Staff listing]. Page accessed August 9, 2015. [http://www.buddhism.hku.hk/staff_info/DrBarryKerzinCV2015.pdf Kerzin CV at HKU Last updated March 2015]. Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> At the [[University of Hong Kong]] he was appointed 'Visiting Professor of Medicine' for 2014 and 2015 and was made an Honorary Professor at the university's Centre of Buddhist Studies in March 2015.<ref name=HKUCV/>  Kerzin is a fellow of the [[Mind & Life Institute]],<ref>Mind & Life Institute. [https://www.mindandlife.org/fellows-programs/ List of Fellows] Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> which was initiated in 1985 to foster a dialogue between Buddhist scholars and Western scientists.<ref>Gay Watson, Beyond happiness: deepening the dialogue between Buddhism, psychotherapy and the mind sciences, Karnac Books, 2008, {{ISBN|1-85575-404-5}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85575-404-1}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=80JNDfdTA2MC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 169]</ref><ref>Barinaga M. Buddhism and neuroscience. Studying the well-trained mind. Science. 2003 Oct 3;302(5642):44-6. {{PMID|14526055}}</ref>\n\n==Works ==\n* '''Publications''': Kerzin is the author of ''No Fear No Death: The Transformative Power of Compassion'' ''N\u0101g\u0101rjuna\u2019s Wisdom: A Practitioner\u2019s Guide to the Middle Way'' (in press); ''The Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness|url=http://books.barrykerzin.org/|publisher=Human Values Institute, Tokyo|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> (in Japanese); ''Mind and Matter: Dialogue between Two Nobel Laureates (in Japanese).'' Furthermore, Kerzin has written many chapters for books and done many interviews for radio and TV, in the US and abroad.\n* '''TEDx Talks''': He delivered a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx talk]], on Happiness in 2010<ref>{{cite web|author1=Barry Kerzin|title=Happiness|url=http://tedxtalks.ted.com/video/TEDxPhoenixville-Barry-Kerzin-H;Lifestyle|publisher=TEDx Phoenixville Salon|date=July 2010|format=Video}}</ref> and one in 2014 on Compassion and Anger Management<ref name=TEDx>{{cite web|title=Barry Kerzin at TEDx Taipei 2014|url=http://tedxtaipei.com/talks/2014-barry-kerzin/|publisher=TEDx Taipei|accessdate=31 March 2015|location=Taipei, Taiwan|format=Video}}</ref>\n*'''Dharma Talks:''' He delivered a dharma talk on Nagarjuna\u2019s Wisdom: The Middle Way for ''[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review]].''\n* '''Documentaries''': Kerzin was featured in the 2006 U.S. [[PBS|Public Broadcasting Service]] documentary entitled The New Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|title=The New Medicine|url=https://www.pbs.org/thenewmedicine/|publisher=PBS|format=Radio programme|date=March 29, 2006}}</ref> This TV documentary received a largely negative review in the Wall Street Journal,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dorothy Rabinowitz|title=The New Medicine|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114315337050506797|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=March 24, 2006}}</ref> but a more positive one appeared in the New York Times.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Charles McGrath|title='The New Medicine' on PBS: Doctors Turn to the Mind for Healing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/29/arts/television/29mcgr.html?_r=2&|publisher=New York Times|date=March 29, 2006}}</ref>\n* Kerzin was also featured in October 2015 in a [[PBS Newshour]] documentary \"Dalai Lama\u2019s American doctor wants more compassion in medicine\"\n*Featured in the March 2020 PBS Podcast ''[https://www.undertoldstories.org/ under-told Stories] [https://www.undertoldstories.org/2020/03/09/podcast-the-dalai-lamas-doctor/ \"The Dalai Lama's Doctor\"]''\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Barry Kerzin}}\n*[https://altruismmedicine.org/  Altruism in Medicine]\n*[https://humanvaluesinstitute.org/ Human Values Institute]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerzin, Barry}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Buddhist teachers]]\n[[Category:Consciousness researchers and theorists]]\n[[Category:Keck School of Medicine of USC alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical person\n| name = Barry Kerzin\n| image = Barry Kerzin, American Professor of Medicine and Buddhist monk.gif\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Barry Michael Kerzin\n| birth_date = November 1, 1947\n| birth_place = Hollywood, USA\n| nationality = American\n| citizenship = [[United States of America]]\n| education = University of California at Berkeley (BA Philosophy) and University of Southern California (MD)\n| occupation = Teacher, physician, and Buddhist monk\n| known_for = Medical doctor to HH Dalai Lama and teacher at the interface of Buddhism and medicine\n| relations =\n| signature = \n| profession = \n| field =\n| work_institutions = Private practice (Ventura County, California)<br>[[University of Washington School of Medicine]] (Assistant Professor)<br>Private practice (charitable, [[Dharamshala]] India)<br>Human Values Institute (Japan)<br>Altruism in Medicine Institute (USA)<br>University of Hong Kong (Honorary)\n| specialism = \n| research_field = \n| prizes =\n| child = \n| module2 = \n|Publications=\"No Fear No Death: The Transformative Power of Compassion\", and \"N\u0101g\u0101rjuna\u2019s Wisdom: A Practitioner\u2019s Guide to the Middle Way\" (in press).\"Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness\", and \"Mind and Matter: Dialogue between Two Nobel Laureates\", in Japanese.}}\n\n'''Barry Michael Kerzin'''(born November 1, 1947) is an American physician and Buddhist monk.  He has lived in [[Dharamshala]] since 1988, and serves as a personal physician to the [[14th Dalai Lama]], along with treating people in the local community, free of charge. Following his ordination as a monk by HH Dalai Lama in January 2003, he has travelled widely, teaching and offering workshops in which he blends Buddhist teaching and his medical training, emphasizing the spiritual and health benefits of meditation and compassion.  He has served as a research participant in neuroscience research into [[Brain activity and meditation|the effects of meditation on the brain]].\n\nKerzin is an Affiliate Professor at the [[University of Washington Tacoma]], a Visiting Professor at the [[Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies|Central Institute of Tibetan Studies]], India, an Honorary Professor at the [[University of Hong Kong|University of Hong Kong (HKU)]], an Honorary Professor at the [[Mongolian National University of Medical Sciences]] (from October 2019), and a former Assistant Professor of Medicine at the [[University of Washington]]. He is a fellow at the [[Mind and Life Institute]] and consults for the [[Max Planck Institute for Medical Research|Max Planck Institute]] in Leipzig on compassion training.\n\nHe is founder and president of the Altruism in Medicine Institute (AIMI) and founder and chairman of the Human Values Institute (HVI) in Japan,\n\n==Early life and education ==\nKerzin was born in Hollywood, California on November 1, 1947.<ref name=Ventura/><ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: Month and day of birth and location at 3:29-3:35.</ref>  When he was young he read a book by [[D.T. Suzuki]]'s World of Zen, which sparked an interest in Buddhism.<ref name=caduc />   Starting at around six, he was plagued by questions of who he was and why he was here; they led him to join a philosophy club in high school and to switch to studying philosophy in college; he had started as a pre-med student.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 4:30-8:20.</ref>  He had wanted to become a doctor and did choose to continue on to medical school, because at the age of eleven he had a [[brain abscess]] that caused him to have seizures and fall into comas; it was eventually treated by a neurosurgeon with four brain surgeries over several years; the experience inspired him to become a doctor so that he could help other people.<ref name=caduc>{{cite web|author1=Yaya Huang |title=Mind the Gap \u2014An Interview with Prof. Barry Kerzin |url=http://www.hkucaduceus.net/Volume%2045/Issue2/int1.html |publisher=HKU Medical Faculty 'Caduceus' magazine 2014 |accessdate=31 March 2015 |location=Hong Kong |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402163838/http://www.hkucaduceus.net/Volume%2045/Issue2/int1.html |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nKerzin received BA in Philosophy from the [[University of California at Berkeley]] and in 1976 he received an MD degree from the [[University of Southern California]].<ref name=USCCN /><ref name=AMIbio/>\n\n==Career==\nKerzin did his residency at [[Ventura County Medical Center]] and practiced family medicine in Ojai, California for seven years.<ref name=Ventura>{{cite news|last=Kim Lamb Gregory|title=Doctor/Tibetan monk returns to Ventura County to speak on mind, body|url=http://www.vcstar.com/news/a-physician-who-is-a-tibetan-monk-returns-to-to|newspaper=Ventura County Star|location=Ventura County, California|date=March 6, 2014|quote=Article says he is 66 years old. His birth year must be 1947 as he was born in November}}</ref>  His mother had died when he was 27, and just after he started working in Ojai, his wife was diagnosed with [[ovarian cancer]]. She died in 1983 and they had no children.<ref name=Ventura/>\n\nHe travelled in India, Sri Lanka, and Nepal for nearly a year, visiting several monasteries.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 8:40 - 9:35</ref>\n\nHe then obtained an appointment as an Assistant Professor of Medicine at the [[University of Washington School of Medicine]] from late 1985 to early 1989.<ref name=Ventura/><ref>[https://in.linkedin.com/pub/barry-kerzin/b6/937/832?trk=seokp_posts_secondary_cluster_res_author_name Barry Kerzin's LinkedIn Profile]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Page accessed August 9, 2015.  Source used for dates.</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1980s, [[B. Alan Wallace]] and the [[Dharma Friendship Foundation]] coaxed a lama from Dharamsala, [[Gen Lamrimpa]], to come to Seattle for two years, and Kerzin served as his driver.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 9:30 - 10:15</ref>  In 1988 Gen Lamrimpa returned to India and Kerzin accompanied him, intending to take a six-month leave of absence from the University of Washington.<ref>Altruism in Medicine. [http://altruismmedicine.org/dr-barry-kerzin-a-personal-journey/ Dr Barry Kerzin: A Personal Journey]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Video: 15:25 - 17:00</ref>  He stayed in Dharamsala when his leave ended, and began providing free medical care to the local community, HH Dalai Lama and other Tibetan lamas.<ref name=Ventura/><ref name=USCCN>{{cite web|url=http://tfm.usc.edu/autumn-2013/class-notes-autumn-2013#1970s |publisher=USCTrojan Family |title=Barry Kerzin MD \u201976 (MED) |accessdate=March 30, 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402152211/http://tfm.usc.edu/autumn-2013/class-notes-autumn-2013 |archivedate=April 2, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=AMIbio/>  He also began studying Buddhism and meditation intensively, and 19 years after he moved there (in the early-2000s), he was ordained in Feb. 2003 as a Bikkshu (Buddhist monk) by HH Dalai Lama, and now cares for him as his doctor.<ref name=Ventura/><ref name=AMIbio/>  Throughout his career, Kerzin has maintained his board certification with the [[American Board of Family Medicine]].<ref name=AMIbio>Altruism in Medicine Institute [http://altruismmedicine.org/about/founder-dr-barry-kerzin/ About Dr. Barry Kerzin] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810131944/http://altruismmedicine.org/about/founder-dr-barry-kerzin/ |date=August 10, 2015 }} Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref>\n\nSince his ordination, Kerzin has been combining his work as a monk and doctor, harmonizing the mind and body, lecturing around the world in Japan, Hong Kong, Russia, Mongolia, Taiwan, Korea, Europe, and North America. He is teaching about the interface between [[medical science|modern medical science]] and [[Buddhism and psychology#Buddhism.27s phenomenological psychology|Buddhist psychology]] and [[Buddhist philosophy#Mahayana|philosophy]], with particular reference to [[altruism]] in medicine and [[secular ethics]] as well as [[Compassion#Buddhism|compassion]], [[Wisdom#Buddhism|wisdom]], [[Meditation#Buddhism|meditation]], death and dying and emotional hygiene (managing anger, jealousy, pride, etc.); he has also participated in neuroscience research on the effect of meditation on the brain.<ref name=caduc /><ref name=AMIbio/>\n\n[[File:Barry Kerzin meditating with EEG for neuroscience research.jpg|thumbnail|left|Kerzin meditating with EEG for neuroscience research]]\nIn the mid-2000s, he served as a research subject in neuroscience research into [[Brain activity and meditation|the effects of meditation on the brain]] led by Richard J Davidson at the [[University of Wisconsin]], as well as at [[Princeton University]].<ref>CNN. [http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0612/16/hcsg.01.html HOUSE CALL WITH DR. SANJAY GUPTA House Call with Dr. Sanjay Gupta. Encore Presentation: Happiness Cure] Aired December 16, 2006</ref> Kerzin has completed many meditation retreats, including a three-year retreat.\n\nKerzin founded the Human Values Institute in Japan in 2010 since teaching there regularly starting in 2007; he serves as chairman of the organization.<ref name=\"HVI\">Human Values Institute. [http://humanvaluesinstitute.org/purpose-methods/ HVI Purpose & Methods] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816015612/http://humanvaluesinstitute.org/purpose-methods/ |date=August 16, 2015 }} Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> The institute publishes books and instructional movies, gives lectures, leads workshops and meditation retreats, holds an annual symposium in Tokyo, and leads pilgrimages on the island of [[Shikoku#Traditions|Shikoku]]; the education focuses on healthy physical and emotional living and handling death compassionately.<ref name=\"HVI\" />  He taught about the [[Heart Sutra]] at the [[Gokoku-ji|Gokokuji Temple]] in Tokyo shortly after the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref>[http://issuu.com/dhardho/docs/thetibetpostinternational Tibet Post International March 32, 2011]. Tibetans and Japanese Hold Prayers for Victims of Tsunami. Page 1 and 6</ref> For HVI, Kerzin also works in juvenile prisons in Japan, and is developing well-being curricula, taught to doctors at [[St. Luke's International Hospital]] in Tokyo, and other hospitals and medical schools in Japan, e.g. Kyoto University, and leads meditation retreats at [[Mount Fuji|Mt. Fuji]].\n\nFor AIMI, Kerzin gave a medical grand rounds lecture on compassion at Stanford Medical Schoo, and the Stanford CCARE], and in July lectured at Surgical Grand Rounds on the science behind meditation to the Ventura County Medical Center, as well as lectured at the [[University of Washington]]. In Spring 2016, he lectured at [[Oxford university|Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] Universities, and U.K. medical schools. Kerzin was the keynote speaker for the White Coast Ceremony for new first-year medical students at the [[University of Louisville School of Medicine]] in 2016 and again in 2018. In Fall 2016 he presented the plenary lecture to 800 Family Doctors at the Family Medicine Education Consortium in Pittsburgh, and in 2018 set the foundation for a Mindfulness-Compassion-Resilience training program for 18,000 nurses at UPMC. In Pittsburgh he was interviewed by many media outlets on his involvement with UPMC, the city of Pittsburgh, and his life mission of teaching mindfulness to doctors, nurses, and other professionals and leaders. One of the articles written on him is ''[https://postindustrial.com/featuredstories/the-dalai-lamas-doctor-has-a-message-for-pittsburgh/ The Dalai Lama's Doctor has a Message for Pittsburgh], ''and during his November 2019 visit, ''[https://pittsburghquarterly.com/pq-people-opinion/pq-opinion/item/2569-holiday-thoughts-from-the-dalai-lama-s-physician.html Holiday Thoughts From The Dalai Lama's Physician].'' In 2019, Kerzin led the 2-day program ''Developing Altruistic Algorithms Based on Buddhist Philosophy for Artificial Intelligence'', held at [[DeepMind]] (an Alphabet Group company) in London, UK.\n\nHe participated in a 2011 weeklong workshop organized by scientists at the [[Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences]] in Leipzig, exploring the role that compassion training has in changing human behavior and emotions.<ref>[http://www.cbs.mpg.de/depts/singer/WorkshopConf Workshop \"How to Train Compassion\" 20.-23. July 2011, Studio Olafur, Berlin]</ref>  The workshop led to a documentary film and a multimedia book to which Kerzin contributed two chapters.<ref>[http://altruismmedicine.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Compassion_Web_2_Chapters.pdf Chapters 4 and 6] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402101215/http://altruismmedicine.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Compassion_Web_2_Chapters.pdf |date=April 2, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kerzin founded the Altruism in Medicine Institute in the US.<ref>[https://opencorporates.com/companies/us_ca/C3624572 Altruism in Medicine Institute in the Open Corporates Database] Page accessed August 9, 2015]</ref>\n\nHe had a visiting professorship at the Central University of Tibetan Studies, Varanasi, India in 2006.<ref name=HKUCV>HKU Centre of Buddhist Studies [http://www.buddhism.hku.hk/teaching_staff.htm Staff listing]. Page accessed August 9, 2015. [http://www.buddhism.hku.hk/staff_info/DrBarryKerzinCV2015.pdf Kerzin CV at HKU Last updated March 2015]. Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> At the [[University of Hong Kong]] he was appointed 'Visiting Professor of Medicine' for 2014 and 2015 and was made an Honorary Professor at the university's Centre of Buddhist Studies in March 2015.<ref name=HKUCV/>  Kerzin is a fellow of the [[Mind & Life Institute]],<ref>Mind & Life Institute. [https://www.mindandlife.org/fellows-programs/ List of Fellows] Page accessed August 9, 2015</ref> which was initiated in 1985 to foster a dialogue between Buddhist scholars and Western scientists.<ref>Gay Watson, Beyond happiness: deepening the dialogue between Buddhism, psychotherapy and the mind sciences, Karnac Books, 2008, {{ISBN|1-85575-404-5}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85575-404-1}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=80JNDfdTA2MC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 169]</ref><ref>Barinaga M. Buddhism and neuroscience. Studying the well-trained mind. Science. 2003 Oct 3;302(5642):44-6. {{PMID|14526055}}</ref>\n\n==Works ==\n* '''Publications''': Kerzin is the author of ''No Fear No Death: The Transformative Power of Compassion'' ''N\u0101g\u0101rjuna\u2019s Wisdom: A Practitioner\u2019s Guide to the Middle Way'' (in press); ''The Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tibetan Buddhist Prescription for Happiness|url=http://books.barrykerzin.org/|publisher=Human Values Institute, Tokyo|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> (in Japanese); ''Mind and Matter: Dialogue between Two Nobel Laureates (in Japanese).'' Furthermore, Kerzin has written many chapters for books and done many interviews for radio and TV, in the US and abroad.\n* '''TEDx Talks''': He delivered a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx talk]], on Happiness in 2010<ref>{{cite web|author1=Barry Kerzin|title=Happiness|url=http://tedxtalks.ted.com/video/TEDxPhoenixville-Barry-Kerzin-H;Lifestyle|publisher=TEDx Phoenixville Salon|date=July 2010|format=Video}}</ref> and one in 2014 on Compassion and Anger Management<ref name=TEDx>{{cite web|title=Barry Kerzin at TEDx Taipei 2014|url=http://tedxtaipei.com/talks/2014-barry-kerzin/|publisher=TEDx Taipei|accessdate=31 March 2015|location=Taipei, Taiwan|format=Video}}</ref>\n*'''Dharma Talks:''' He delivered a dharma talk on Nagarjuna\u2019s Wisdom: The Middle Way for ''[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review]].''\n* '''Documentaries''': Kerzin was featured in the 2006 U.S. [[PBS|Public Broadcasting Service]] documentary entitled The New Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|title=The New Medicine|url=https://www.pbs.org/thenewmedicine/|publisher=PBS|format=Radio programme|date=March 29, 2006}}</ref> This TV documentary received a largely negative review in the Wall Street Journal,<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dorothy Rabinowitz|title=The New Medicine|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114315337050506797|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=March 24, 2006}}</ref> but a more positive one appeared in the New York Times.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Charles McGrath|title='The New Medicine' on PBS: Doctors Turn to the Mind for Healing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/29/arts/television/29mcgr.html?_r=2&|publisher=New York Times|date=March 29, 2006}}</ref>\n* Kerzin was also featured in October 2015 in a [[PBS Newshour]] documentary \"Dalai Lama\u2019s American doctor wants more compassion in medicine\"\n*Featured in the March 2020 PBS Podcast ''[https://www.undertoldstories.org/ under-told Stories] [https://www.undertoldstories.org/2020/03/09/podcast-the-dalai-lamas-doctor/ \"The Dalai Lama's Doctor\"]''\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Barry Kerzin}}\n*[https://altruismmedicine.org/  Altruism in Medicine]\n*[https://humanvaluesinstitute.org/ Human Values Institute]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerzin, Barry}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Tibetan Buddhists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Buddhist teachers]]\n[[Category:Consciousness researchers and theorists]]\n[[Category:Keck School of Medicine of USC alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Berlineye", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a commentary written in response to an article on JAMA in 2020.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Kerzin"}
{"title_page": "Frank S. Black", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. He was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine|Limington, York County, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His father moved the family to [[Alfred, Maine]] after accepting an appointment as keeper of the [[York County, Maine|York County]] jail.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, then taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875, was an editor of all three of the school's student publications, and won prizes for oratory.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}} While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved [[Rome, New York]], where he sold [[Chromolithography|Chromolithographs]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He soon moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A member of the [[Half-Breeds (politics)|Half-Breed]] faction of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and follower of [[James G. Blaine]],{{sfn|''Bulletin to the Schools''}} Black changed the political stance of the paper while its Democratic owner was out of town, for which he was promptly fired.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], where he worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and ''Troy Times''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} While working as a night reporter, he was a clerk in the Troy post office and [[reading law|studied law]] with the firm of Robertson & Foster.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted. McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as a result of the Ross murder case, in November 1894, Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the Committee on Private Land Claims.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nAs governor, Black advocated for conservation of the area now known as the [[Adirondack State Park]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} As part of this effort, he oversaw the establishment of the [[History of the New York State College of Forestry]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During Black's governorship, the boroughs that now make up [[New York City]] were consolidated into one municipality.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nBlack also oversaw New York's participation in the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Under his leadership, 16,000 soldiers were raised, trained, and equipped for accession into the [[United States Army]] as it expanded for the war.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In addition, he successfully advocated for election reforms, including allowing soldiers to vote while they out of state or outside the United States.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1896, Black had been nominated for governor by Republican political operative Louis F. Payn, who was widely regarded as a corrupt associate of [[Thomas C. Platt]], the boss of New York State's Republican Party. As governor, Black caused a controversy when appointed Payn as [[New York State Insurance Department|state insurance superintendent]]. Despite criticism from advocates of good government and civil service reform, Black continued to support Payn. Despite backing Payn, Black incurred Platt's displeasure when Black successfully opposed a bill Platt favored, which would have banned from newspapers editorial cartoons critical of state government officials.\n\nLate in Black's term, state officials were accused of squandering more than a million dollars on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs. Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]]. Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]]. In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.\n\n==Later life==\nAfterwards he resumed his law practice. Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case. After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial. The case was the source of the well-known \"Molineux rule\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office. In 1904, he was a candidate for the Republican nomination for [[United States Senator]], but lost to incumbent [[Chauncey Depew]], who went on to win reelection. He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term. In 1908, Black supported William Howard Taft for president.\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913. He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his farm outside [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school in Provincetown. They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Cutter |editor-first=William Richard |date=1918 |title=American Biography: A New Cyclopedia |volume=II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmoKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA347 |location=New York, NY |publisher=The American Historical Society |pages=347-348 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''American Biography''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |date=1890 |title=Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Feo140qPrb4C&pg=PA675 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Council Publishing Company |page=675 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}}}\n\n===Magazines===\n*{{cite magazine |date=September 15, 1923 |title=Governors of New York: Frank S. Black, 1897-98 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U1QwAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA61 |magazine=Bulletin to the Schools |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The University of the State of New York |page=61 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Bulletin to the Schools''}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n*{{Findagrave|6848745}}\n*[https://www.nga.org/governor/frank-swett-black/ Biography, Frank Swett Black] at National Governors Association\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]] |\n  after=[[Aaron V. S. Cochrane]] |\n  years=1895\u20131897\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Governor of New York]] | before = [[Levi P. Morton]] | after = [[Theodore Roosevelt]] | years = 1897\u20131898}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Frank Swett}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Limington, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Burials in New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. He was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine|Limington, York County, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His father moved the family to [[Alfred, Maine]] after accepting an appointment as keeper of the [[York County, Maine|York County]] jail.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, the taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875, was an editor of all three of the school's student publications, and won prizes for oratory.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}} While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved [[Rome, New York]], where he sold [[Chromolithography|Chromolithographs]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He soon moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A member of the [[Half-Breeds (politics)|Half-Breed]] faction of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and follower of [[James G. Blaine]],{{sfn|''Bulletin to the Schools''}} Black changed the political stance of the paper while its Democratic owner was out of town, for which he was promptly fired.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], where he worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and ''Troy Times''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} While working as a night reporter, he was a clerk in the Troy post office and [[reading law|studied law]] with the firm of Robertson & Foster.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted. McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as a result of the Ross murder case, in November 1894, Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the Committee on Private Land Claims.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nAs governor, Black advocated for conservation of the area now known as the [[Adirondack State Park]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} As part of this effort, he oversaw the establishment of the [[History of the New York State College of Forestry]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During Black's governorship, the boroughs that now make up [[New York City]] were consolidated into one municipality.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nBlack also oversaw New York's participation in the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Under his leadership, 16,000 soldiers were raised, trained, and equipped for accession into the [[United States Army]] as it expanded for the war.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In addition, he successfully advocated for election reforms, including allowing soldiers to vote while they out of state or outside the United States.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1896, Black had been nominated for governor by Republican political operative Louis F. Payn, who was widely regarded as a corrupt associate of [[Thomas C. Platt]], the boss of New York State's Republican Party. As governor, Black caused a controversy when appointed Payn as [[New York State Insurance Department|state insurance superintendent]]. Despite criticism from advocates of good government and civil service reform, Black continued to support Payn. Despite backing Payn, Black incurred Platt's displeasure when Black successfully opposed a bill Platt favored, which would have banned from newspapers editorial cartoons critical of state government officials.\n\nLate in Black's term, state officials were accused of squandering more than a million dollars on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs. Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]]. Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]]. In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.\n\n==Later life==\nAfterwards he resumed his law practice. Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case. After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial. The case was the source of the well-known \"Molineux rule\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office. In 1904, he was a candidate for the Republican nomination for [[United States Senator]], but lost to incumbent [[Chauncey Depew]], who went on to win reelection. He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term. In 1908, Black supported William Howard Taft for president.\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913. He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his farm outside [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school in Provincetown. They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Cutter |editor-first=William Richard |date=1918 |title=American Biography: A New Cyclopedia |volume=II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmoKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA347 |location=New York, NY |publisher=The American Historical Society |pages=347-348 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''American Biography''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |date=1890 |title=Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Feo140qPrb4C&pg=PA675 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Council Publishing Company |page=675 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}}}\n\n===Magazines===\n*{{cite magazine |date=September 15, 1923 |title=Governors of New York: Frank S. Black, 1897-98 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U1QwAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA61 |magazine=Bulletin to the Schools |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The University of the State of New York |page=61 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Bulletin to the Schools''}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n*{{Findagrave|6848745}}\n*[https://www.nga.org/governor/frank-swett-black/ Biography, Frank Swett Black] at National Governors Association\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]]